Q: Altitudes $\overline{AX}$ and $\overline{BY}$ of acute triangle $ABC$ intersect at $H$.  If $\angle AHB = 132^\circ$, then what is $\angle ACB$?

solution:
First, we build a diagram:

[asy]

size(150); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));

pair B = (0,0), C = (3,0), A = (1.4,2), P = foot(A,B,C), Q = foot(B,A,C),H = intersectionpoint(B--Q,A--P);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);

draw(A--P^^B--Q);

label("$A$",A,N); label("$B$",B,W); label("$C$",C,E); label("$X$",P,S); label("$Y$",Q,E); label("$H$",H,NW);

draw(rightanglemark(C,P,H,3.5));

draw(rightanglemark(H,Q,C,3.5));

[/asy]

From quadrilateral $CXHY$, we have  \begin{align*}
\angle ACB = \angle XCY &= 360^\circ - \angle HXC - \angle YHX - \angle CYH \\
&= 360^\circ - 90^\circ - \angle YHX - 90^\circ\\
&= 180^\circ - \angle YHX.
\end{align*}Since $\angle YHX = \angle AHB$, we have $\angle ACB = 180^\circ - \angle YHX = \boxed{48^\circ}$.

